Intro to Differential Equations: Solving separable equations, Euler’s method, and direction fields

Author

H Elliott

Some basic examination of differential equations and their solutions.

Also a brief demonstration of Euler’s method for approximation of solutions.

Euler’s method function

#' Perform Euler's method to approximate the solution to an initial value problem
#' 
#' @param f The function defining the differential equation dy/dt = f(t, y), with
#'     signature `function(t, y)`
#' @param y0 The initial value of y at t0
#' @param t0 The initial value of t
#' @param t1 The final value of t
#' @param h The step size to take from t0 to t1
eulers <- function(f, y0, t0, t1, h) {
    t <- seq(t0, t1, by = h)
    y <- numeric(length(t))
    y[1] <- y0
    t[1] <- t0
    for (i in 2:length(t)) {
        y[i] <- y[i - 1] + h * f(t[i - 1], y[i - 1])
    }
    return(list(t = t, y = y, f = f, y0 = y0, t0 = t0, t1 = t1, h = h))
}

# plotting functions
plot_eulers <- function(eulers_result, true_f = NULL, legend_pos = "topleft") {
    plot(eulers_result$t, eulers_result$y,
         type = "p", cex = 0.5, col = rgb(0, 0, 0, 0.5),
         main = "Euler's method results",
         sub = paste(deparse(eulers_result$f), collapse = ""),
         xlab = "t", ylab = "y")
    lines(eulers_result$t, eulers_result$y, col = rgb(0, 0, 0, 0.5))
    if (! is.null(true_f)) {
        tlin <- seq(res$t0, res$t1, by = 0.01)
        lines(tlin, true_f(tlin), col = "red")
    }
    if (legend_pos != "none") {
        legend(legend_pos, legend = c("Euler's method", "Exact solution"),
               col = c("black", "red"),
               lty = 1)
    }
}


#' plot direction field
#' f: differential equation function with signature `function(t, y)`
plot_directionfield <- function(f,
                                t_range = c(-5, 5),
                                y_range = c(-5, 5),
                                radius = 0.1, grid.by = 0.25, alpha = 1){
    # credit:
    # https://stackoverflow.com/questions/47984874/how-to-create-a-slope-field-in-r
    
    # initial plot - ensure large enough
    plot(t_range, y_range,
         main = "Direction field", ylab = "y", xlab = "t",
         pch = ".")
    # plot arrows
    tlin = seq(min(t_range), max(t_range), grid.by)
    ylin = seq(min(y_range), max(y_range), grid.by)
    for(x in tlin) {
        for(y in ylin) {
            slope = f(x, y)
            if(is.na(slope)) {
                col = rgb(0, 0, 0, alpha)
            } else if(slope > 0) {
                col = rgb(0, 0, 1, alpha)
            } else if (slope < 0) {
                col = rgb(1, 0, 0, alpha)
            } else if(slope == 0) {
                col = rgb(0, 1, 0, alpha)
            }
            arrows(radius * cos(atan(slope) + pi) + x,
                   radius * sin(atan(slope) + pi) + y,
                   radius * cos(atan(slope)) + x,
                   radius * sin(atan(slope)) + y, 
                   length = 0.2 * radius, col = col)
        }
    }
}

Example 1

The differential equation \[\frac{dy}{dt} = t (4 - y)\] has general solution \[y = 4 + C e^{-t^2/2}\] where \(C\) is a constant.

Derivation:

  • \(\frac{dy}{4-y} = t dt\)
  • \(\int \frac{dy}{4-y} = \int t dt\)
  • \(- \ln|4 - y| = \frac{t^2}{2} + C_0\)
  • \(\ln|4 - y| = -\frac{t^2}{2} + C_1\)
  • \(|4 - y| = e^{-t^2/2} e^{C_1}\)
  • \(4 - y = \pm e^{-t^2/2} e^{C_1}\)
  • \(y = 4 \pm e^{-t^2/2} e^{C_1}\)
  • \(y = 4 + C e^{-t^2/2}\) where \(C = \pm e^{C_1}\) is a constant.

One solution to the differential equation is \(y = 4\) so that \(\frac{dy}{dt} = 0\) for all \(t\). This is satisfied if \(C = 0\). Other particular solutions depend on the initial condition.

If \(y(0) = 0\), then \(C = -4\) and the solution is \[y = 4 - 4 e^{-t^2/2}\]

f <- \(t, y) t * (4 - y)
true_sol <- \(t) 4 - 4 * exp( (-t^2) / 2) # if y(t = 0) = 0

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
for (stepsize in c(0.5, 0.1, 0.05, 0.01)) {
    res <- eulers(f, y0 = 0, t0 = 0, t1 = 4, h = stepsize)
    plot_eulers(res, true_sol, legend_pos = "none")
    abline(h = 4, col = "blue", lty = 2)
    mtext(side=3, line=0.5, at=-0.01, adj=0, cex=0.7,
          paste("step size = ", res$h))
}

Note that the red lines show the exact solution and the black points/lines show the approximated solution via Euler’s method.

A different initial condition:

If \(y(0) = 8\), then \(C = 4\) and the solution is \[y = 4 + 4 e^{-t^2/2}\]

f <- \(t, y) t * (4 - y)
true_sol <- \(t) 4 + 4 * exp( (-t^2) / 2) # if y < 4 and y(t = 0) = 0

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
for (stepsize in c(0.5, 0.1, 0.05, 0.01)) {
    res <- eulers(f, y0 = 8, t0 = 0, t1 = 4, h = stepsize)
    plot_eulers(res, true_sol, legend_pos = "none")
    abline(h = 4, col = "blue", lty = 2)
    mtext(side=3, line=0.5, at=-0.01, adj=0, cex=0.7,
          paste("step size = ", res$h))
}

Notice that in both cases, the solutions seems to converge to \(y = 4\) (the blue dashed line) as \(t\) increases. This is because \(y = 4\) is a stable solution to the differential equation.
This can be seen by plotting the direction field of the differential equation.
The black lines plot the particular solutions examined above. Each solution is tangent to the direction field at every point.

plot_directionfield(f,
                    t_range = c(-5, 5), y_range = c(0, 8),
                    alpha = 0.5)
mtext(side=3, line=0.5, at=-3, adj=0, cex=0.7,
      "dy/dt = t(4 - y), and solutions for y(0) = 0 and y(0) = 8")

tlin <- seq(-5, 5, 0.01)
lines(tlin, 4 - 4 * exp( (-tlin^2) / 2) , col = "black", lty = 1)
lines(tlin, 4 + 4 * exp( (-tlin^2) / 2) , col = "black", lty = 1)

Example 2

Here is another simple example.
Differential equation \[\frac{dy}{dt} = y\] has general solution \[y = C e^t\] where \(C\) is a constant:

  • \(\frac{dy}{y} = dt\)
  • \(\int \frac{dy}{y} = \int dt\)
  • \(\ln|y| = t + C_0\)
  • \(|y| = e^{t + C_0}\)
  • \(y = \pm e^{t}e^{C_0}\)
  • \(y = C e^t\) where \(C = \pm e^{C_0}\) is a constant.

Notice that if If \(y = 0\) then \(\frac{dy}{dt} = 0\) for all \(t\), and this is achieved when \(C = 0\). Otherwise the particular solution depends on the initial condition.

If \(y(t = 0) = 2\), \(C = 2\) and the particular solution is \(y = 2 e^t\).
Generally, for this simple equation if we start at \(t = 0\), whatever the value of \(y(0)\) is will be the value of \(C\). Here are some plots for different initial conditions.

f <- \(t, y) y
true_sol <- \(t, y0) y0 * exp(t)

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
tlin <- seq(0, 4, by = 0.01)
for (y0 in c(-2, -1, 1, 2)) {
    plot(tlin, true_sol(tlin, y0), type = "l", col = "red",
         main = paste("Exact solution when y(0) = ", y0),
         sub = paste("y =", y0, "* exp(t)"),
         xlab = "t", ylab = "y")
    abline(h = 0, col = "blue", lty = 2)
}

In this case, the solution \(y = 0\) is unstable because solutions that start near \(y = 0\) will tend move away from it as \(t\) increases.

plot_directionfield(f,
                    t_range = c(-5, 5), y_range = c(-5, 5),
                    alpha = 0.5)
mtext(side=3, line=0.5, at=-3, adj=0, cex=0.7,
      "dy/dt = y, and solutions for y(0) = 1 and y(0) = -1")

tlin <- seq(-5, 5, 0.01)
lines(tlin, 1 * exp(tlin) , col = "black", lty = 1)
lines(tlin, -1 * exp(tlin) , col = "black", lty = 1)

Some first-order ODEs and their direction fields from applications

Newton’s law of cooling or heating

The change in the temperature of an object, which we will denote as \(y\), over time, \(t\) converges to the temperature of its surroundings, or “room temperature”, \(R\).
The parameter \(k\) is the “cooling rate”, which depends on the object.

The differential equation is: \[\frac{dy}{dt} = -k (y - R)\]

Solving:

  • \(\frac{-1}{k} \frac{dy}{R - y} = dt\)
  • \(\int \frac{-1}{k} \frac{dy}{R - y} = \int dt\)
  • \(\frac{-1}{k} \ln|R - y| = t + C_0\)
  • \(\ln|R - y| = -k t + C_1\)
  • \(|R - y| = e^{-kt + C_1}\)
  • \(R - y = \pm e^{C_1} e^{-kt}\)
  • \(y = R \pm e^{C_1} e^{-kt}\)
  • \(y = R + A e^{-kt}\) where \(A = \pm e^{C_1}\) is a constant.

Generally, if the initial condition is that \(y(t = 0) = y_0\), then \(y_0 = R + Ae^0\) and so \(A = y_0 - R\).

So if the initial temperature of the object, \(y_0\), is greater than the room temperature, the object will cool down. Otherwise, it will heat up. And when \(y = R\), the object has reached the room temperature, and from the differential equation we can see that \(\frac{dy}{dt} = 0\), so the object will stay at room temp.

# Newton's law of cooling or heating
# y = temperature of the object
# R = room temperature/temperature of the surroundings
# k = the cooling rate (object-dependent), k > 0
make_diffeq <- \(R, k) return( \(t, y) -k * (y - R) )

# plot direction field
plot_directionfield(f = make_diffeq(R = 5, k = 0.5),
                    t_range = c(0, 10), y_range = c(4, 8))


sol <- \(t, A, R, k) R + A * exp(-k * t)
# y(0) = 10, R = 5 # (object is cooling down to R)
tlin <- seq(0, 10, 0.01)
lines(tlin, sol(tlin, A = 5, R = 5, k = 0.5), col = "black", lty = 1)
# y(0) = 0, R = 5  # (object is warming up to R)
tlin <- seq(0, 10, 0.01)
lines(tlin, sol(tlin, A = -5, R = 5, k = 0.5), col = "black", lty = 1)

Infection in a population

The change in the size of the infected population, \(y\), over time, \(t\), with total population, \(P\), is given by:

\[\frac{dy}{dt} = k y (P - y)\]

This can be though of as being proportional to the number of infected people (\(y\)) times the number of uninfected people in the population (\(P - y\)), where \(k\) is a constant that acts like an “infection rate” for the particular disease.

This is a separable equation so it can be solved - you need to use partial fractions to integrate (steps shown below).
The solution: \[y = \frac{P C e^{Pkt}}{1 + C e^{Pkt}}\].
The particular solutions are logistic curves, as you can tell by their S-shape.

\(C\) is a constant that will depend on the initial condition.

If \(y(t = 0) = 1\) (one infected person at time 0), then \(1 = \frac{P C}{1 + C}\) so \(C = \frac{1}{P - 1}\).

make_diffeq <- \(P, k) return( \(t, y) k * y * (P - y) )

# solution when y(0) = 1:
sol <- \(t, P, k, C) {
    e_pkt <- exp(P * k * t)
    (P * C * e_pkt) / (1 + C * e_pkt)
} 

# plot direction field
plot_directionfield(f = make_diffeq(P = 10, k = 0.1),
                    t_range = c(0, 10), y_range = c(0, 12))
mtext(side=3, line=0.5, at=0, adj=0, cex=0.7,
      paste("Initial population =", 10))

# plot solution for a few different infection rates
tlin <- seq(0, 10, 0.01)
lines(tlin, sol(tlin, P = 10, k = 0.05, C = 1/9), col = "black", lty = 1)
lines(tlin, sol(tlin, P = 10, k = 0.1, C = 1/9), col = "black", lty = 1)
lines(tlin, sol(tlin, P = 10, k = 0.3, C = 1/9), col = "black", lty = 1)

Solving the differential equation:

  • \(\frac{dy}{dt} = k y (P - y)\)
  • \(\frac{dy}{y (P - y)} = k dt\)
  • \(\int \frac{dy}{y (P - y)} = \int k dt\)
    • \(\frac{1}{y(P - y)} = \frac{A(P -y) + By}{y(P-y)} = \frac{(B-A)y + AP}{y(P-y)}\)
    • so \(B - A = 0 \Rightarrow A = B\)
    • and \(AP = 1 \Rightarrow A = B = \frac{1}{P}\)
    • so \(\int \frac{dy}{y (P-y)} = 1/P \int dy/y + 1/P \int dy/(P-y) dy\)
  • \(\frac{1}{P} \ln|y/(P-y)| = kt + C_0\)
  • \(\ln|y/(P-y)| = Pkt + C_0P\)
  • \(y/(P-y) = \pm e^{Pkt + C_0P} = y / (P - y) = Ce^{Pkt}\), where \(C = \pm e^{C_0P}\)
  • \(y = (P-y)Ce^{Pkt} = PC{e^{Pkt}} - yCe^{Pkt}\)
  • \(y + yCe^{Pkt} = PC{e^{Pkt}}\)
  • \(y(1 + Ce^{Pkt}) = PC{e^{Pkt}}\)
  • \(y = \frac{P C e^{Pkt}}{1 + C e^{Pkt}}\)

Some random direction fields

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
plot_directionfield(f = \(y, t) t + y)
plot_directionfield(f = \(t, y) sin(t * y))

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
plot_directionfield(f = \(t, y) sin(t) * y)
plot_directionfield(f = \(t, y) sin(t) * y + cos(t))

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
plot_directionfield(f = \(y, t) sin(t) + cos(y))
plot_directionfield(f = \(y, t) sin(t) + cos(y) + y)
